  "prompt": "How do I find an engine for an SAE Supra?",
  "response": "Finding an engine for your SAE Supra vehicle requires a bit of research and consideration. Here's a breakdown of how to approach it:\n\n**1. Understand the Regulations & Your Design:**\n\n*   **SAE Supra Rules:**  The single most important thing!  **You MUST adhere to the SAE Supra rules for engine selection.**  These rules are typically found in the official SAE Collegiate Design Series rules documentation.  **These rules change YEARLY!  Always reference the rulebook for the year you are competing.**  Pay very close attention to the engine displacement limit, any restrictions on forced induction, fuel type, and any requirements regarding engine management systems.\n*   **Your Team's Capabilities:**  Assess your team's technical expertise.  Can you handle complex modifications, custom engine mounts, wiring, and tuning? Are you comfortable with fuel injection or carburation? This will influence your engine choice.\n*   **Vehicle Design:** Consider your car's overall design.  What weight target are you aiming for?  How much space is available in the engine bay?  What is the planned drivetrain configuration (transmission, gearing)?  Engine choice significantly affects all of this.\n\n**2. Common Engine Choices (Historically - but check current rules!):**\n\n*   **Briggs & Stratton Vanguard 10 HP, 12 HP, 14 HP:** These are the most common choices, for a few reasons:\n    *   **Readily Available:**  You can typically find them new from Briggs & Stratton dealers or used from go-kart racers and equipment suppliers.\n    *   **Affordable:** Generally cheaper than other alternatives.\n    *   **Parts Availability:**  Aftermarket performance parts are widely available.\n    *   **Reliable:**  Relatively robust engines.\n    *   **Lightweight:** Compared to other engine types.\n*   **Honda GX Series (GX270, GX390):**  Another popular option:\n    *   **Reliable:** Honda is known for reliability.\n    *   **Good Performance:**  Can be tuned for decent power.\n    *   **Parts Support:**  Excellent aftermarket parts availability.\n    *   **More Expensive:** Usually pricier than the Briggs.\n*   **Kohler Command Pro Series:** Similar considerations to the Honda GX series.\n*   **Modified Snowmobile Engines (less common now):**  In the past, some teams experimented with small displacement snowmobile engines.  While potentially offering more power, they often require significant modification and can be heavier and less reliable.  *Highly unlikely to be legal under current rules.*\n*   **Other Single Cylinder Engines:** Consider other engines of similar displacement from manufacturers like Predator.\n\n**3. Sourcing Your Engine:**\n\n*   **New Engines:**\n    *   **Briggs & Stratton Dealers:**  The official route for Vanguard engines.\n    *   **Honda/Kohler Dealers:**  For GX or Command Pro series engines.\n    *   **Online Retailers:**  Places like Amazon, eBay, etc., can sometimes have new engines, but carefully verify the seller's reputation.\n*   **Used Engines:**\n    *   **Go-Kart Racing Forums/Suppliers:** Go-kart racers often upgrade engines, so you might find used engines for sale.\n    *   **Lawnmower/Equipment Repair Shops:**  They might have used engines from damaged equipment.\n    *   **Online Marketplaces (eBay, Craigslist, Facebook Marketplace):**  Be cautious when buying used. Thoroughly inspect the engine before purchase. Ask about its history, and try to see it running if possible.\n    *   **SAE Supra Alumni:**  Reach out to teams that have competed in the past. They may have spare engines or valuable advice.\n*   **Engine Suppliers Specializing in SAE Supra:**  Some suppliers specialize in parts and engines for SAE Supra competitions.  Search online for \"SAE Supra engine suppliers\" or similar terms.\n\n**4. Engine Research & Preparation:**\n\n*   **Download the Engine's Service Manual:**  Essential for understanding engine maintenance, troubleshooting, and modification.  Most manufacturers have them available online.\n*   **Research Available Aftermarket Parts:**  Even if you plan to run the engine stock, know what performance parts are available.  This can help you improve reliability or address specific design requirements.\n*   **Plan Your Engine Modifications (if allowed):**  If the rules and your team's expertise allow, plan any engine modifications carefully.  Examples include:\n    *   **Intake/Exhaust Modifications:** To improve airflow.\n    *   **Carburetor Tuning/Fuel Injection:** To optimize fuel delivery.\n    *   **Camshaft Upgrades:** To alter valve timing.\n    *   **Head Work:** Porting and polishing.\n*   **Consider Data Acquisition:**  Plan to collect data (engine temperature, RPM, etc.) during testing and competition to help optimize performance and troubleshoot problems.\n\n**5. Things to Consider Before Buying:**\n\n*   **Condition:**  If buying used, inspect for damage, wear, and evidence of poor maintenance.  Check compression and look for signs of oil leaks.\n*   **Completeness:**  Does the engine come with all necessary components (carburetor, starter, ignition system, etc.)?\n*   **Price:**  Compare prices from different sources.  Consider the cost of any necessary repairs or modifications.\n*   **Shipping:**  Factor in shipping costs, especially for heavier engines.\n*   **Rule Compliance:**  *Reiterate: ABSOLUTELY ENSURE THE ENGINE MEETS ALL CURRENT SAE SUPRA RULES.*  Don't waste your money on an engine you can't legally use.\n\n**Important Tips:**\n\n*   **Start Early:**  Don't wait until the last minute to find an engine.  Give yourself plenty of time for research, sourcing, and preparation.\n*   **Network with Other Teams:**  Talk to other SAE Supra teams about their engine choices and experiences.  They can offer valuable advice and insights.\n*   **Document Everything:** Keep detailed records of your engine research, purchases, modifications, and testing.  This will help you troubleshoot problems and improve your performance.\n*   **Prioritize Reliability:** A reliable engine is more important than ultimate power. A DNF (Did Not Finish) due to engine failure is a major setback.\n\nBy following these steps and paying close attention to the SAE Supra rules, you can find an engine that will help your team succeed in the competition. Good luck!\n",
